The paper deals with algorithms for constructing e-nets and e-approximations of streams of geometric data, and using them to answer geometric queries on data streams. This falls under the category of computational geometry (cs.CG) and data structures and algorithms (cs.DS). The paper also discusses robust statistics of geometric data streams, which can be considered as a subfield of data mining (cs.DM) and databases (cs.DB). Finally, the paper includes a lower bound for noniceberg geometric queries, which is related to computational geometry and computational complexity (cs.ST).
